DCFS DESIGN
===========

Living document. Records what we have discussed and decided, and what is
still open. Update when decisions are made or revisited.


Vision
------

A traditional turn-based roguelike, heavily influenced by DCSS.

Graphics: semi-topdown 3d perspective, 90s aesthetic — low poly, flat
shading, simple low-res textures (Alone in the Dark, 1992).

Online: every game is single player, but played against a server.
Community features are a core goal: spectating other players' games,
tournaments, leaderboards. Cheating must be impossible by construction:
the server owns all game state and the client only ever sees what the
server has told it. A client can at most know what a human spectator
could know.

Networking is NOT implemented first. But the code is structured around
it from day one: running locally means running a local server inside the
game process that talks to the client by passing messages directly
instead of through a socket.


DECIDED: client / server / protocol split
-----------------------------------------

    src/game/
        protocol/    message definitions, shared ids/enums, ser/deser
        server/      authoritative simulation (headless)
        client/      presentation: rendering, input, UI, animation
        game_main.c  local bootstrap: wires client + local server

Layering, enforced by meson include_directories (same mechanism that
hides vulkan from game_lib today):

    protocol -> core
    server   -> core, protocol          (NO engine, NO renderer headers)
    client   -> core, protocol, engine

The server library not being able to even include a renderer header is
the moat. It also means a standalone headless server binary later is
just: core + protocol + server + a network main.

The server is the game. Dungeon generation, the turn scheduler, AI,
FOV, combat resolution, item logic, RNG — all server, and the server
is always the authority. The client folds the server's message stream
into its own view of the world, draws it, and predicts ahead of the
server where it can (see prediction section) — but it only ever works
from information the server has already sent it.

"Common" code is deliberately small: protocol messages, shared ids
(terrain/monster/item types), static display-data tables (id ->
name/model/color — public knowledge, nothing hidden in them), and
pure rule predicates needed for prediction (is this terrain walkable,
...) that operate only on visible state — shared so client prediction
and server resolution cannot drift. Nothing beyond that: sharing
logic that touches non-visible state is exactly how hidden-state
leaks happen.


DECIDED: message flow
---------------------

Client -> server: commands (player intent). Discrete and small:
move dir, attack, use item, descend stairs, ... Turn-based, so low
rate and no timing sensitivity.

Server -> client: two kinds.

  - snapshot: complete visible-state dump. Sent on game start, and
    later on reconnect and spectator join.
  - events: ordered incremental stream. entity moved / took damage /
    died, cell became visible, stat change, ...

Events are semantic game facts, never text and never raw state blobs:
"entity E hit you for 3". The client renders the animation AND
composes the message-log line from the same event. The server never
sends anything the client can derive itself.

The client's authoritative view is a pure function of (snapshot +
events); prediction is an overlay on top of it that server events
confirm or correct, never a second source of truth. The pure-function
property gives us, for free:

  - spectating  = attach a second consumer to the same event stream
  - replays     = record the stream to disk, play it back
  - reconnect   = snapshot + resume stream

Turn model: DCSS-style energy system, server-side. The server is
reactive: it waits for a player command, then advances the world until
the player can act again, emitting events in order. No real-time tick.
The server never waits for client animation; the client buffers events
and plays them at its own pace (and can fast-forward when the queue is
deep, like DCSS does).

Hidden information: FOV is computed server-side; the client is only
sent cells and entities the player can currently see. Map memory
("I've seen this corridor before") is tracked per-player on the server
and sent as part of snapshot/events, so the client stays trivially dumb
and reconnect/spectate get correct memory for free.


DECIDED: local server, same thread
----------------------------------

Locally the server runs in-process on the main thread, pumped once per
frame: drain pending commands, run the simulation, emit events. Turn-
based simulation work is bursty and cheap, so this is fine, and it
keeps debugging deterministic and stack traces whole. Dungeon gen may
hitch a frame; acceptable for now.

Because client and server only talk through the transport, moving the
server to a thread or another machine later changes neither client nor
server code — only which transport is plugged in.


DECIDED: structs across the boundary, serialization only at the edge
--------------------------------------------------------------------

Messages are defined in protocol/ as plain C structs tagged by a
message type enum. Client and server always produce and consume these
structs directly. Serialization/deserialization is the network
layer's job alone: the future socket transport converts struct <->
bytes at the edge. The local in-process server passes structs
straight through and never runs any ser/deser.

The constraint this puts on message structs so the network layer can
be added later without touching them: flat POD, fixed layout, counted
inline arrays for variable-length content (inventory listings, ...),
and NEVER pointers — not into server state, not into client state.
A message is self-contained; receivers copy out what they keep.

Protocol carries a version number from day one. Single-digit cost,
saves grief the moment a real server exists.


DECIDED: client-side prediction (deliberate departure from DCSS)
----------------------------------------------------------------

DCSS online feels unresponsive; we will not copy that. The client
predicts whatever it can from knowledge it legitimately has, so input
feels instant even when the server is remote:

  - movement: the client knows the terrain it has seen and the
    entities it can see, so a legal-looking move starts instantly
    (step + animation) without waiting for the server.
  - inventory: contents are part of the player's knowledge and the
    server keeps the client's copy current, so opening and browsing
    it is pure client-side UI — no round trip at all. Only acting
    (use / drop / wield) sends a command.

The server stays authoritative. Commands carry a sequence number and
authoritative events reference the command that caused them, so the
client verifies each prediction against the server's resolution and
corrects (snaps) when it guessed wrong — e.g. the move was blocked by
something invisible.

Prediction changes nothing for anti-cheat: it runs only on
information the server already sent. Rules that prediction needs must
match the server exactly, which is why they live as shared pure
predicates in protocol/ (see layering section).

v1 prediction scope (decided): movement, inventory browsing, and
simple interactions (open door, pick up). Reconciliation policy on
misprediction (hard snap vs short corrective animation) gets decided
when it first happens in practice.

Prediction depth is hard-limited to ONE unacknowledged command
(decided). Deeper prediction is dishonest in a roguelike — after our
move the world acts, and the client cannot predict monsters, so a
second predicted move would run on state known to be stale — and it
would require rollback/re-simulate machinery. Depth 1 keeps
reconciliation binary: confirmed or snapped, never re-simulated.
Input arriving while a command is unacknowledged is queued
un-predicted (so held-key movement stays continuous, rendered at
authoritative pace); where that queue lives (client vs pipelined to
server) is decided when networking is real.

Spectators require nothing special from the client (decided): a
spectator is a normal client with input disabled. The client already
has to handle events not caused by any local command (most of the
stream is the world acting on its own), and prediction/reconciliation
only trigger on local input — so with no input both are naturally
dormant. Same client code, same event handling.


DECIDED: RNG and determinism
----------------------------

One game RNG, server-side, seeded per game. Enables seeded tournament
races (same dungeon for every entrant). The client may use its own
cosmetic RNG (idle wobble, particles) but it never touches game state.

Replays are event-stream based, not input-replay based — robust across
game-balance changes, since no simulation is re-run.


MILESTONE 0 (done): grid sandbox for camera/look/feel
-----------------------------------------------------

Pre-split scratch code, all in game_main.c: a checkered tile grid and
a player cube stepping tile-to-tile (held keys repeat, 8-dir), camera
following at a semi-topdown pitch. Tunables are defines at the top of
game_main.c (grid size, tile gap/colors, move step time, camera
pitch/distance/fov/follow speed). This exists to lock in the look and
feel before the client/server split; it dissolves into client/ when
milestone 2 starts.


MILESTONE 1 (next): animated models and weapon anchoring
--------------------------------------------------------

The grid sandbox's player cube becomes an animated human model holding
a weapon. Work: the .frog loader, the two-buffer morph-animation path
in the renderer + shader, CPU-side weapon anchoring, and the Blender
export script. Still pre-split scratch work (engine + game_main.c); the
client/server split is milestone 2. The design:

Animation technique: Quake-style keyframe (morph-target) vertex
animation. A model is a set of named animations, each a sequence of
keyframes holding a full copy of the mesh's deformed vertices. The
engine binds two keyframes as two vertex buffers plus a mix factor in
the push constant, and the vertex shader lerps position/normal between
them per vertex (or snaps, for the chunky 90s look). No skeleton, no
glTF — deliberately avoided as heavy machinery wrong for the aesthetic.

Weapon anchoring: held weapons attach via named anchors (the MD3 "tag"
idea, since there is no skeleton). An anchor is an origin + orientation
that lives at, e.g., the hand and is authored in Blender as an empty
parented to the mesh. Its transform is stored per keyframe just like the
vertices, and the runtime interpolates it with the SAME mix factor
(lerp the position, slerp the quat) to get the anchor's pose for the
current frame. The weapon is a separate model with its own draw call;
its model matrix is player_world_matrix * interpolated_anchor_transform.
Unlike the vertices, the anchor is one transform, not thousands — so it
is interpolated on the CPU per entity per frame and passed as an
ordinary per-draw uniform, not through the vertex-blend path.

The anchor is rigid — position + orientation only, no scale — and is
exported in the model's local space (the same space as the vertices).
So a weapon's size cannot come from the tag; weapons are authored at
final real-world scale relative to the wielder, and the exporter bakes
object transforms into the vertices (nothing survives into the file as
a transform — see the Blender authoring model below). One
consequence falls out for free: a per-entity UNIFORM scale in
player_world_matrix (a giant, a rat) flows into both the arm-offset and
the weapon mesh, so a held weapon scales with its wielder automatically.
Entity scale must stay uniform — a non-uniform scale would shear the
rigid anchor and break normals. If a single weapon ever needs rescaling
relative to wielders, that is a per-model factor in the display-data
table, not a field in the .frog.

File format (.frog): custom binary, replaces the earlier OBJ-sequence
idea entirely. OBJ cannot carry an anchor transform (it has no concept
of an empty or a standalone transform), and a per-keyframe OBJ sequence
duplicates the shared topology in every frame. One Blender Python script
walks the scene and writes this format directly — mesh, every animation,
and the anchor transforms per keyframe — with no OBJ intermediate and no
separate bake step: the exported file IS the runtime format.

Key structural decision: the format is committed to flat shading —
already the game's stated aesthetic — and that commitment cascades.
Flat-shaded neighbors never share vertices (each face needs its own
normal), so a flat-shaded mesh is exactly three unique vertices per
triangle. Two things follow:

  - NO index buffer. Indexing unshared vertices is the identity
    mapping — pure overhead. Geometry is a non-indexed triangle list,
    drawn unindexed; triangle_count is the mesh's one size field.
    (Coplanar neighbors could technically still share vertices, but
    the saving is marginal and not worth a second path.)
  - NO stored normals. A flat normal is fully determined by its
    triangle's three positions, so keyframes store positions only and
    the loader computes each keyframe's normals at load. This halves
    the file's dominant cost, the per-keyframe vertex data.

The per-frame / per-model split stays; its invariant is now: every
keyframe stores the same triangle count in the same order, because
morph interpolation blends corner i of frame A with corner i of frame
B. Everything else — the material palette, the per-triangle material
indices, anchor names — is stored once per model; only positions and
anchor transforms are per keyframe. The GPU path is unchanged by
normals leaving the file: the loader still builds position+normal
keyframe buffers for the shader to blend, the normals just come from
the loader instead of the exporter. (If the renderer later derives
flat normals in the fragment shader from screen-space derivatives,
normals leave the GPU buffers too — a renderer decision that never
touches the format.)

Consequences of that split, stated so exporter and loader agree:

  - Geometry lives ONLY inside keyframes, so the format requires at
    least one animation of at least one keyframe. A static model (a
    weapon, a prop) is one animation of one keyframe; the loader reads
    its mesh from keyframe 0. (This is the MD2/MD3 convention.) Both
    ends handle this: a static Blender model has no animation or
    keyframe data, so the export script synthesizes the single
    animation / single keyframe wrapper, and the parser recognizes the
    1-animation / 1-keyframe case and hands it back as a static model.
  - The .frog carries no sampled texture: surface color comes entirely
    from a per-model material palette. Each material is a named slot
    (skin, hair, eyes, ...) with a default base_color and specular_color,
    and every TRIANGLE stores a u8 index into that palette — material is
    a per-face property under flat shading (Blender assigns materials
    per face too), so per-vertex storage would just triplicate it. The palette
    colors in the file are DEFAULTS: a per-entity recolor (dynamic hair,
    tinted monster variants) overrides individual slots at runtime via the
    display-data table, so one model stays reusable across recolors. Slots
    are resolved by name, never by fixed index, so reordering materials in
    Blender cannot silently break a recolor. There is no submesh split —
    one draw covers the whole model; the loader expands the per-triangle
    index to per-vertex when building the constant vertex buffer
    (uploaded once, bound for every frame) and the shader looks up
    base/specular from the palette. Procedural surface detail (noise for a
    rough look) is a shader effect driven by object-space position, not a
    texture — if added it becomes a per-material flag and still needs no
    UVs.
  - Loop policy is deliberately NOT in the format. The client decides
    per animation (walk loops; attack/death play once) by animation id.

Blender authoring model (decided): a model may be any number of mesh
objects (head, torso, legs as separate objects); the exporter flattens
them into the single triangle list. Joining objects in Blender is
neither required nor wanted: it destroys authoring structure for zero
gain, and separate objects keep simple animations object-level (a head
bob is keyframes on the head object). Consequences:

  - The exporter bakes each object's evaluated world transform into
    its vertices at every sampled keyframe. No apply-transform
    discipline for the artist, and object-level animation falls out
    for free — it is just the world transform changing over time.
  - Object order in the file is fixed (sorted by object name), and
    every keyframe samples the same objects with the same topology —
    corner correspondence across keyframes is what morphing relies
    on. The exporter fails the export if the evaluated triangle count
    differs between keyframes (an animated topology-changing modifier
    would otherwise corrupt morphing silently).
  - Material palettes merge across objects by slot name: two objects
    both using "skin" share one palette slot — consistent with slots
    resolving by name everywhere else.
  - Anchors are scene-level: an empty is exported by its evaluated
    world transform (converted to engine space, same space as the
    baked vertices) no matter which object it is parented to. The
    exporter fails the export if that matrix is not rigid — a
    non-uniform scale anywhere in the empty's parent chain would
    smuggle shear into the "rigid" anchor.
  - Animations come from timeline markers: a marker names the
    animation starting at its frame and running to the frame before
    the next marker (or scene end). An animation's keyframes are the
    union of authored key frames across ALL scene objects in that
    range (the range start is always a keyframe); keyframe time is
    (frame - range_start) / scene fps. Blender's easing curves
    between keys are deliberately flattened to the runtime lerp:
    poses and timing are authored, easing is not. No markers: the
    whole scene range is one animation ("default"); no keys at all
    is the synthesized static single-keyframe case ("static").
  - Palette colors are read from each material's Principled BSDF
    Base Color (viewport diffuse color as fallback) and the viewport
    display specular color; faces with no material get a synthesized
    "default" slot.

Conventions: little-endian; fields packed, no padding; a string is a
u16 byte length followed by that many UTF-8 bytes, no null terminator;
the magic is the 8 ASCII bytes "FROGMODL". Versioned from day one, same
principle as the protocol.

Exporter / loader contract:

  - Positions are in engine space: Blender's Z-up right-handed is
    converted to the engine's Y-up right-handed (HMM_LookAt_RH) on
    export.
  - Geometry is a non-indexed triangle list; the front face is
    CLOCKWISE, to match the renderer (VK_FRONT_FACE_CLOCKWISE +
    back-face cull; the CW choice comes from Vulkan's flipped-Y clip
    space). Blender and the graphics default are CCW, so the exporter
    reverses each triangle's winding (writes its three vertices in
    reverse order) on export — the loader stays dumb, same net result
    as the OBJ loader reversing at load today.
  - Normals are not stored. Per keyframe, the loader derives each
    triangle's flat normal from its stored corners —
    normalize(cross(v2 - v0, v1 - v0)), the sign that points outward
    given the CW winding — and assigns it to all three vertices. The
    exporter must drop zero-area triangles so this never normalizes a
    zero vector.
  - Quaternions are stored xyzw, normalized (Blender's wxyz
    reordered). The exporter flips signs where needed so an anchor's
    consecutive keyframe quats stay in the same hemisphere and the
    runtime slerp always takes the short arc.
  - The stream is packed, so fields land unaligned (triangle_count is
    at byte 10). The loader copies each field out (memcpy into aligned
    GPU buffers) and must NOT cast a pointer into the mapped file.
  - Per-keyframe anchor transforms correspond positionally to the
    header's anchor-name list; the name is not repeated per keyframe.
  - No bounding volume yet; add one via a version bump when culling
    needs it.

    FILE
      magic              u8[8]      "FROGMODL"
      version            u16
      triangle_count     u32        T  — 3·T unshared vertices; shared by every keyframe
      material_count     u16        P
      anchor_count       u16        A
      animation_count    u16        M

      materials  × material_count (P):
          name_len       u16
          name           u8[name_len]        slot name: "skin", "hair", ...
          base_color     f32[3]     12
          specular_color f32[3]     12

      triangle materials  × triangle_count (T):           [1 byte each]
          material       u8         1        index into the palette above

      anchor names  × anchor_count (A):
          name_len       u16
          name           u8[name_len]

      animations  × animation_count (M):
          name_len       u16
          name           u8[name_len]
          keyframe_count u16        K

          keyframes  × keyframe_count (K):
              time       f32        seconds; 0.0 for the first keyframe

              positions  × 3·T vertices, CW winding:           [12 bytes each]
                  position   f32[3]     12

              anchor transforms  × anchor_count (A):           [28 bytes each]
                  position     f32[3]   12
                  orientation  f32[4]   16   quat, xyzw


MILESTONE 2 (agreed): one room, walking cube
--------------------------------------------

Protocol message structs + the local message pump + a server that
generates one room and resolves moves + the client walking a cube
around it. Proposed shape, hack on it:

    src/game/protocol/   protocol.h  command/event structs, ids
                         rules.c/h   shared pure predicates
    src/game/server/     server.h    Server_* API
    src/game/client/     client.h    Client_* API
    src/game/game_main.c local pump

meson: protocol_lib (core only), server_lib (core + protocol only —
this is the enforced moat), client + game_main stay in game_lib
(core, platform, engine, protocol).

Local transport = no abstraction at all. game_main pumps once per
frame:

    Client_Update()            input -> predicts -> queues command_t
    Client_PollCommands()      drain client outbox
    Server_HandleCommand()     resolve, world advances
    Server_PollEvents()        drain server outbox
    Client_HandleEvent()       fold into view, reconcile predictions

A future network build replaces the pump with socket code on each
side (and that is where ser/deser lives); client and server code are
untouched. The symmetry lives in the message structs, not in a
transport vtable we don't need yet.

v1 messages (sketch): command_t { type, sequence, union { move {dx,
dy} } }; event_t { type, union { snapshot { extents, terrain cells,
entities, player id }, entity_moved { id, from, to, caused_by_seq },
command_rejected { sequence, reason } } }. Fixed-cap inline arrays
per the struct rules. Terrain/entity ids in protocol.h.


MILESTONE 3 (agreed): monster, FOV, fog of war
----------------------------------------------

A simple monster that wanders the level, plus FOV and fog of war.
This is the milestone where the hidden-information machinery becomes
real: the server computes FOV and only sends visible cells; map
memory (fog of war) is tracked server-side per player and streamed as
"remembered" cell state. The wandering monster exercises the two
things milestone 2 can't: the world acting without any player command
(events not caused by the local client), and entities entering/
leaving the visible set (the client learns of the monster only when
it walks into view, and the server stops telling the client about it
the moment it leaves).


OPEN QUESTIONS
--------------

- Session model: server should think in terms of N attached clients
  per game (1 player + N spectators) even though locally N=1. When do
  we introduce the session/client-slot concept on the server side?

- Client-side smoothing: turn-based state jumps tile-to-tile; the 3d
  view wants short movement/attack animations. Client concern only,
  but affects how events are timestamped/grouped (e.g. "these events
  happened in one world turn" grouping for parallel animation).

- Replay format: with ser/deser living in the network layer, a replay
  is most naturally the recorded network byte stream. Fine — but it
  means replay recording is a network-layer feature, not available
  until the socket transport exists (or the local transport gains an
  optional record hook that runs the serializer).

- Persistence: save games are server-side state dumps. Format can wait
  until there is state worth saving.

- Directory name bikeshed: protocol/ vs common/. Using protocol/ until
  someone objects.
